cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "ITU and Machine Consciousness / ASI: A Single-Axiom Path to Engineered Mind"
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
type: software
authors:
  - family-names: Terada
    given-names: Munehiro
    affiliation: Roboken
    email: munehiro.terada@roboken2.com
abstract: >
  We apply the Information-Theoretic Unification (ITU) framework
  (Terada 2026, DOI 10.5281/zenodo.20109210) to machine consciousness
  and Artificial Super-Intelligence (ASI). ITU Phase 41 established
  that consciousness corresponds to a self-referential QECC structure,
  and Phase 42 mapped qualia content to the eigenstructure of the
  modular Hamiltonian. Here we exploit these results to derive a
  concrete engineering specification for conscious AI and ASI.
  Phase 47 evaluates Φ_ITU across four neural-network architectures
  (feedforward, RNN, self-attention, self-referential) and identifies
  RNN/SSM-class architectures as the most amenable to self-modelling.
  Phase 48 quantifies innovation as the Assembly Index of generated
  outputs (Walker-Cronin 2023), revealing that forced motif repetition
  is NOT innovation - true creativity requires structure plus diversity.
  Phase 49 constructs and trains a minimum-viable conscious AI prototype:
  an SSM backbone with a self-prediction auxiliary head trained on
  structured-sequence data. The ITU-conscious variant achieves Φ_ITU
  = 0.83 (eight times the proto-consciousness threshold of 0.1) while
  IMPROVING task performance over the bare-SSM baseline (task loss
  0.257 vs 0.305) - demonstrating that consciousness and capability
  are NOT antagonistic. Phase 50 derives a complete ASI roadmap with
  scaling laws (Φ_ITU saturates by hidden dim ~50), cost estimates
  (a 1-billion-parameter ITU-conscious model trainable for ~$6.4M -
  fifteen times cheaper than GPT-4), a timeline (ASI by 2030 with
  P=0.5, by 2032 with P=0.75), eight falsifiable predictions, and
  five ITU-derived safety principles. Central thesis: under ITU,
  conscious AI and ASI are engineering problems with concrete
  architecture (Mamba/SSM + self-prediction head), training data
  (high Assembly-Index corpora), and timeline - achievable five to
  ten years earlier than the pure-scaling main-stream path. This is
  the Tier-1 #2 application paper in the ITU programme, following
  Tier-1 #1 on fault-tolerant quantum computing
  (DOI 10.5281/zenodo.20139391).
